<!-- §9 What is red light therapy -->
<h2 style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">What is Red Light Therapy?</h2>
<p style="color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Red light therapy (RLT) is the use of specific wavelengths of red (600–700nm) and infrared (800–1100nm) light to stimulate cellular energy production and trigger biological healing responses. Unlike harsh UV light or lasers, red and infrared wavelengths are non-ionizing and non-thermal at consumer irradiance levels.</p>
<p style="color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Red light primarily affects skin: it boosts collagen, reduces inflammation, and supports wound healing. Infrared penetrates deeper into muscles, tendons, and joints, supporting recovery and reducing pain. Clinical studies have documented benefits for wound healing, post-surgical recovery, muscle soreness, and skin conditions. However, consumer devices operate at lower power density than clinical panels, so results scale accordingly.</p>
<p style="color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">Red light therapy isn't magic, and it's not a medical treatment—it's a supportive tool backed by legitimate science. Most benefits compound with consistent use over weeks, not immediate relief.</p>

