    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">How does it compare to LED face masks like Moor Glo or Project E Beauty?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">LED face masks ($70–$150) are designed exclusively for facial skin therapy. This portable device is more versatile—you can use it on face, joints, muscles, or anywhere you have pain or skin issues. Face masks are convenient and hands-free for face-only applications. This instrument wins on flexibility and targeting scope, though neither matches clinical-grade panels in power. Choose based on your needs: just facial therapy? Face mask. Multi-area treatment? This device.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">How long before I see results from red light therapy?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Results vary by application. Muscle soreness and inflammation often improve within 1–3 weeks of consistent use. Skin improvements (collagen, texture, wound healing) typically take 4–8 weeks. Some users report joint pain relief within 2–3 weeks. Consistency matters more than frequency—aim for 3–5 sessions weekly rather than occasional long sessions. Most clinical studies used 8+ weeks of consistent therapy, so be patient and track your progress weekly.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">Is it safe to use red light therapy every day?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Yes, when used as directed per your manual. Red and infrared light are non-ionizing and non-thermal at consumer power levels, making them safe for daily use. Start with 3–5 sessions per week to assess your individual response, then increase to daily use if well-tolerated. Avoid direct unprotected eye exposure (unless your device is designated as eye-safe). Do not use on skin conditions that react poorly to heat without consulting a healthcare provider first.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">What's the difference between red light (600–700nm) and infrared (800–1100nm)?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Red light has shorter wavelengths, so it absorbs in upper skin layers, supporting collagen production, wound healing, and skin texture. Infrared has longer wavelengths and penetrates deeper into muscles, tendons, joints, and bone, supporting recovery and pain relief. This device combines both wavelengths for a broader therapeutic range—red for skin, infrared for deep tissue. For maximum benefit, use consistently so both can work synergistically.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">Can I use this to replace dermatology or physical therapy?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">No. Red light therapy is a supportive wellness tool, not a medical treatment. If you have serious skin conditions (eczema, psoriasis, acne requiring Accutane), joint injuries, or chronic pain, consult a dermatologist or physical therapist first. Red light therapy can complement professional treatment—many clinics use it alongside PT or dermatology—but it's not a replacement. Think of it as a recovery support tool, not a primary intervention.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">Can I use it while on acne medication?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Consult your dermatologist first, especially if you're on retinoids, isotretinoin, or photosensitizing medications. Red light is generally gentle, but combined with certain treatments, it might cause unexpected reactions. Getting professional guidance ensures you can safely combine treatments without complications.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">How far should I hold it from my face?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Most consumer devices recommend 6–12 inches from skin. Check your specific device's manual for the optimal distance. Too close may cause discomfort; too far reduces intensity. The sweet spot is where you feel gentle warmth without heat stress. Some devices have adjustable distance recommendations.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">Will it work on darker skin tones?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Red light penetrates through different skin tones similarly, though deeper skin tones may require slightly longer exposure for equivalent benefits. The wavelength (660nm) works universally. Individual skin types and sensitivities vary more than skin tone. If concerned, start with shorter sessions and gradually increase.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">Can I use it daily?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Yes, daily use is safe. Many users use it 5-7 days per week for 10-20 minute sessions. Some people prefer daily use; others find 3-4 times weekly sufficient. Listen to your skin—if irritation occurs, reduce frequency. Most benefits are cumulative with consistent use over weeks.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details style="padding: 1rem; background: var(--muted); border-radius: var(--radius); cursor: pointer;">
    <summary style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--foreground); user-select: none;">Does it work for anti-aging?</summary>
    <div style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--foreground); line-height: 1.6;">
      <p style="margin: 0;">Red light may support skin health and potentially stimulate collagen production, which theoretically could help with fine lines and skin texture. However, this device isn't a substitute for retinoids, sunscreen, or professional treatments. Use it as a complementary wellness tool for overall skin support, not as primary anti-aging therapy.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
</div>

